{% extends "base.html.j2" %}
{% block title %}About / Validation &middot; WBB RAPM{% endblock %}
{% block content %}
<div class="panel">
  <h2>What is RAPM?</h2>
  <p>RAPM (regularized adjusted plus-minus) measures each player's impact on point margin
  per 100 possessions, <b>adjusted for everyone else on the floor</b>. Every constant-lineup
  stint of every game becomes a regression row: the five players on each side are the
  predictors and the stint's scoring margin is the outcome. Because all ten on-court players
  enter each row, a player gets no credit for riding great teammates and no penalty for
  facing great opponents &mdash; the regression separates those effects.</p>
  <p>The model is a <b>ridge regression</b>: a penalty &lambda; (chosen by cross-validation,
  grouped by game so no game leaks across folds) shrinks every coefficient toward zero.
  Low-minute players have little evidence to push against the prior, so they land near
  average instead of topping the leaderboard on a lucky 30 minutes &mdash; that is the point
  of the regularization. Players under {{ low_minutes_flag }} minutes are additionally
  flagged and hidden by default.</p>
  <p><b>ORAPM / DRAPM</b> come from a second model with two rows per stint (one per side's
  offense), giving each player separate offensive and defensive impacts; RAPM = ORAPM + DRAPM.
  Non-D1 opponents (exhibitions, buy games) are collapsed into a single shared column so they
  cannot distort D1 ratings.</p>
  <p class="muted small">Caveat: players who almost always share the floor (or almost never
  play apart from a star) are hard to separate statistically; ridge keeps them stable but
  their O/D splits deserve skepticism.</p>
</div>

<div class="panel">
  <h2>Pipeline validation &mdash; {{ season_label }}</h2>
  {% if coverage_note %}<p class="small muted" style="margin-top:-4px">&#9888; {{ coverage_note }}</p>{% endif %}
  <div class="statgrid">
    <div class="stat"><div class="v">{{ '%.2f'|format(v.team_sanity.pearson_rapm_vs_net_margin) }}</div>
      <div class="k">corr: team RAPM vs net margin</div></div>
    <div class="stat"><div class="v">{{ '%.2f'|format(v.team_sanity.pearson_rapm_vs_win_pct) }}</div>
      <div class="k">corr: team RAPM vs win%</div></div>
    <div class="stat"><div class="v">{{ '%.2f'|format(v.lineups.mean_mae_minutes) }}</div>
      <div class="k">minute reconciliation MAE</div></div>
    <div class="stat"><div class="v">{{ v.lineups.n_excluded }}/{{ v.lineups.n_games }}</div>
      <div class="k">games excluded (QA)</div></div>
    <div class="stat"><div class="v">{{ '{:,}'.format(v.model.n_stints|int) }}</div>
      <div class="k">stints in model</div></div>
    <div class="stat"><div class="v">{{ '%.1f'|format(v.model.hca_margin) }}</div>
      <div class="k">home-court adv (pts/100)</div></div>
  </div>
  <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:12px">
  Lineups are reconstructed from ESPN play-by-play substitution events and validated by
  comparing each player's reconstructed floor time to her official box-score minutes; games
  exceeding {{ v.lineups.threshold }} min mean absolute error per player are excluded.
  The team check aggregates player RAPM (minute-weighted) per team and confirms that good
  teams rate higher &mdash; positive correlation with both scoring margin and winning percentage.
  Ridge &lambda;: {{ v.model.lam_margin|int }} (margin model), {{ v.model.lam_od|int }} (O/D model).</p>
</div>

<div class="panel">
  <h2>Season availability</h2>
  <p class="small">Lineup-based RAPM needs substitution events, and ESPN's women's
  college basketball play-by-play only began recording them during the 2024&ndash;25
  season (from February 12, 2025). That means 2025&ndash;26 has full-season coverage,
  2024&ndash;25 covers late-season play only (flagged above), and 2023&ndash;24 and
  earlier cannot be rated with this method &mdash; no substitution data exists in the feed.</p>
</div>

<div class="panel">
  <h2>Build</h2>
  <p class="small">Data is pulled with <a href="https://wehoop.sportsdataverse.org/">wehoop</a> (R),
  modeled with scikit-learn ridge regression (Python), and rendered to this fully static site.
  Re-run any season with <code>make season YEAR=&lt;year&gt;</code>.</p>
</div>
{% endblock %}
